The paper deals with information theory and capacity achieving input distributions for discrete memoryless channels, which are typically studied in the field of information theory (cs.IT). The paper also discusses sufficient conditions for a discrete distribution to be a capacity achieving input distribution, which could fall under the sub-category of information theory and probability (cs.ITP). The concept of capacity achieving distributions is also relevant to the study of computational complexity (cs.CC), as it relates to the efficiency of communication protocols. The paper's focus on discrete memoryless channels and input/output alphabets suggests a connection to discrete structures (cs.DS). Lastly, the paper's discussion of output distributions could potentially fall under the sub-category of social and information networks (cs.SI), as it relates to the distribution of information in a network.
